---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Aside from '../../../components/Aside.astro';
import {monkoSidebar} from '../../../data/monko-sidebar';
import {Code} from 'astro:components';
---

<DocsLayout title="Entity Model" sidebar={monkoSidebar} description="Stored, New, Ref, LazyRef — the Vault wrappers">

    <h1>Entity Model</h1>

    <p class="text-xl text-gray-400 !mt-2 !mb-8">
        Your data classes stay clean. Database metadata lives in wrappers.
    </p>

    <p>Monko uses the same entity model as <a href="/ultra/karango/entity-model">Karango</a> &mdash;
        the <code>Storable&lt;T&gt;</code> hierarchy from the shared Vault module.
        This means you can switch between MongoDB and ArangoDB without changing your domain classes.</p>

    <h2>The wrapper types</h2>

    <div class="not-prose my-8">
        <table class="w-full text-sm text-left">
            <thead>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/10">
                <th class="py-2 text-gray-400">Type</th>
                <th class="py-2 text-gray-400">When to use</th>
                <th class="py-2 text-gray-400">Has value?</th>
                <th class="py-2 text-gray-400">Has ID?</th>
            </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/10">
                <td class="py-2 text-white"><code>New&lt;T&gt;</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-gray-400">Entity not yet persisted</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-gray-400">Yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-gray-400">Empty until inserted</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/10">
                <td class="py-2 text-white"><code>Stored&lt;T&gt;</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-gray-400">Loaded from or saved to database</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-gray-400">Yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-gray-400">Yes (<code>_id</code>, <code>_key</code>)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/10">
                <td class="py-2 text-white"><code>Ref&lt;T&gt;</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-gray-400">Eager entity reference</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-gray-400">Yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-gray-400">Yes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/10">
                <td class="py-2 text-white"><code>LazyRef&lt;T&gt;</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-gray-400">Lazy entity reference</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-gray-400">Loaded on demand</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-gray-400">Yes</td>
            </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <h2>Defining entities</h2>

    <p>Annotate with <code>@Vault</code>. Your data class contains only domain fields.
        The wrapper adds <code>_id</code>, <code>_key</code>, and <code>_rev</code>.</p>

    <Code code={`@Vault
data class Person(
    val name: String,
    val age: Int,
    val email: String,
    val address: Address = Address(),
)

@Vault
data class Address(
    val city: String = "",
    val zip: String = "",
    val country: String = "",
)`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>Working with Stored</h2>

    <Code code={`val stored: Stored<Person> = repo.insert("key-1", Person("Alice", 30, "alice@example.com"))

// Access metadata
stored._id      // "persons/key-1"
stored._key     // "key-1"
stored.value    // Person(name="Alice", age=30, ...)

// Modify (creates new Stored with same metadata)
val updated = stored.modify { copy(age = 31) }
repo.save(updated)

// Map to a different type
val nameOnly = stored.map { it.name }  // Stored<String>

// Identity checks
stored.hasSameIdAs(other)
stored.hasIdIn(listOf(other1, other2))`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <Aside>The wrapper pattern keeps your domain model free of database concerns.
        <code>Person</code> is a plain data class. <code>Stored&lt;Person&gt;</code> adds the database identity.
    </Aside>

    <h2>MongoDB document IDs</h2>

    <p>Monko generates MongoDB document IDs as follows:</p>

    <ul>
        <li>If you provide a key via <code>insert(key, value)</code>, the document gets <code>_id =
            "collection/key"</code></li>
        <li>If no key is provided, Monko generates an <code>ObjectId</code> and converts it to a hex string</li>
        <li>The <code>_key</code> is always the portion after the slash in <code>_id</code></li>
    </ul>

    <div class="mt-12">
        <a href="/ultra/monko/query-dsl"
           class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-6 py-3 rounded-lg bg-brand-400/10 text-brand-400 border border-brand-400/30 hover:bg-brand-400/20 transition-all font-medium">
            Query DSL &rarr;
        </a>
    </div>

</DocsLayout>
